Barring any unforeseen circumstances, Abia State will be locked down today. This followed a directive by an inter-ministerial committee on COVID-19 constituted by Governor Okezie Ikpeazu. The directive which was signed by five top government officials and obtained by LEADERSHIP said inter-state boundaries and markets will be closed for an initial period of one week in the first instance. “Within this period, the people are expected to stay at home with only food and grocery sellers allowed to operate in front of their houses. Further guidance will be issued in this direction in due course,” the committee  said. “We strongly encourage the people to maintain good hygiene through regular washing of hands with soap and running water, use of original hand sanitizers when available as well as maintenance of social distancing is strongly advised,” it said. In preparation for the lockdown, the governor has approved the setting up of a food security sub-committee to plan necessary palliative interventions in case of a prolonged period. However,  there has been panic purchase of foodstuffs and essential commodies, just as queues are gradually returning to the petrol stations while the marketers are yet to reduce the price of fuel as directed by the federal government.